    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="822"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d822">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.419/8–2449</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. <persName type="from">Livingston T.
                            Merchant</persName> of the Office of Far Eastern Affairs to the Chief of
                        the Division of Chinese Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sprouse</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-24">August 24,
                            1949</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Rusk<note n="59" xml:id="d822fn59">Dean Rusk, Deputy Under Secretary of
                        State.</note> indicated to me this afternoon that the President is moving
                    rapidly toward an attitude and policy with respect to Communist China which will
                    result in an abandonment of the thesis <pb facs="0881" n="871" xml:id="pg_871"/>
                    contained in NSC 41.<note n="60" xml:id="d822fn60">February 28, <ref
                            target="#pg_826">p. 826</ref>.</note> It apparently is still his desire
                    to prevent the American tankers from delivering oil to Manchuria.<note n="61"
                        xml:id="d822fn61">For correspondence on this subject, see <ref
                            target="#pg_1002">pp. 1002</ref> ff.</note> We are also immediately
                    instructed to explore in more concrete terms the possibility of aid to Li and
                        Pai.<note n="62" xml:id="d822fn62">Marshal Li Tsung-jen was Acting President
                        of the Republic of China, and General Pai Chung-hsi was his principal
                        military supporter. For correspondence on military aid, see <ref
                            target="#pg_472">pp. 472</ref> ff.</note> In this connection I think you
                    should attempt urgently to reach Kavanaugh of CalTex and ask him to drag his
                    feet on the fuel oil contract for Shanghai.</p>
            </div>
